[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

259
00:18:19,826 --> 00:18:23,293
See, I don't understand
why she persists in, um...

260
00:18:25,293 --> 00:18:27,325
I mean, look at me.
Just take a look at me.

261
00:18:27,458 --> 00:18:28,892
Um...

262
00:18:29,026 --> 00:18:31,559
- Paul.
- That's right, Paul.

263
00:18:31,692 --> 00:18:34,625
Take a good look at me.
I can still manage on my own.

264
00:18:34,759 --> 00:18:36,026
[CHUCKLES]

265
00:18:36,159 --> 00:18:37,725
Don't you think?

266
00:18:37,859 --> 00:18:40,226
I mean,
I'm not, uh, completely...

267
00:18:40,358 --> 00:18:42,725
[LAUGHS]

268
00:18:42,859 --> 00:18:44,659
You agree?
Of course you agree.

269
00:18:44,792 --> 00:18:46,959
But, um, her.

270
00:18:47,092 --> 00:18:49,059
Ah...

271
00:18:49,193 --> 00:18:52,625
I don't know where this, uh,
stupid obsession comes from.

272
00:18:52,759 --> 00:18:56,592
Uh, she's always been that way,
ever since she was little.

273
00:18:56,725 --> 00:18:58,826
Thing is,
she's not very bright.

274
00:19:00,092 --> 00:19:03,092
You know,
she's not very, um...

275
00:19:03,226 --> 00:19:06,358
Not very intelligent.
She gets that from her mother.

276
00:19:06,492 --> 00:19:09,358
I think she tries to do the best
she can for you, Anthony.

277
00:19:09,492 --> 00:19:12,592
Oh, the best she can,
the best she can, yeah.

278
00:19:12,725 --> 00:19:15,525
I never asked her
for anything.

279
00:19:15,659 --> 00:19:17,826
I don't know what
she's cooking up against me,

280
00:19:17,959 --> 00:19:19,425
but she's cooking something up.

281
00:19:19,559 --> 00:19:22,425
She's cooking something up,
that I do know.

282
00:19:22,559 --> 00:19:25,458
See, I suspect she wants
to put me in a home for, um...

283
00:19:25,592 --> 00:19:28,026
[GROANS, THEN CHUCKLING]

284
00:19:29,325 --> 00:19:31,126
Ah, yes,
I've seen the signs.

285
00:19:32,525 --> 00:19:35,659
But let me be
absolutely clear.

286
00:19:36,692 --> 00:19:39,525
I am not leaving my flat.

287
00:19:39,659 --> 00:19:41,892
[YELLS]
I am not leaving my flat!

288
00:19:44,926 --> 00:19:48,492
- This isn't <i>your</i> flat, Anthony.
- Sorry?

289
00:19:48,625 --> 00:19:50,692
If you remember,
you moved here...

290
00:19:50,826 --> 00:19:53,026
You moved to our place
while you were waiting...

291
00:19:53,159 --> 00:19:56,126
- For what?
- For a new carer.

292
00:19:56,259 --> 00:19:58,193
Because you quarreled
with the last one.

293
00:19:58,325 --> 00:20:00,325
- With Angela.
- Oh, did I?

294
00:20:00,458 --> 00:20:03,026
That's why you're staying
in our place while you wait.

295
00:20:04,425 --> 00:20:06,492
- So, James...
- Paul.

296
00:20:06,625 --> 00:20:08,792
Right, Paul.

297
00:20:08,926 --> 00:20:12,358
So you're telling me
this is your place?

298
00:20:12,492 --> 00:20:14,358
Yes.

299
00:20:14,492 --> 00:20:16,458
Ah, now I've heard everything.

300
00:20:18,992 --> 00:20:20,458
- It's me.
- Ah, there she is.

301
00:20:20,592 --> 00:20:21,826
[DOOR CLOSES]

302
00:20:24,392 --> 00:20:26,525
- What's happening?
- PAUL: Oh, nothing much.

303
00:20:26,659 --> 00:20:29,159
Your father seemed
a bit confused.

304
00:20:29,293 --> 00:20:30,959
Is something wrong?

305
00:20:31,092 --> 00:20:32,392
Uh...

306
00:20:33,525 --> 00:20:35,293
What is this nonsense?

307
00:20:35,425 --> 00:20:37,059
What are you talking about?

308
00:20:37,193 --> 00:20:38,959
[♪♪♪]

309
00:20:39,092 --> 00:20:40,358
[STAMMERS]

310
00:20:40,492 --> 00:20:42,692
Where's Anne?

311
00:20:42,826 --> 00:20:43,859
Sorry?

312
00:20:43,992 --> 00:20:45,959
Anne. Where is she?

313
00:20:47,293 --> 00:20:49,392
I'm here.

314
00:20:49,525 --> 00:20:52,159
I just went down to do
some shopping. I'm back now.

315
00:20:52,992 --> 00:20:54,892
[♪♪♪]

316
00:20:56,992 --> 00:20:58,193
Oh, I see.

317
00:21:02,325 --> 00:21:03,425
[CHUCKLES]

318
00:21:04,625 --> 00:21:05,959
What did you buy?

319
00:21:06,092 --> 00:21:08,492
Chicken. Does that sound good?
Are you hungry?

320
00:21:08,625 --> 00:21:10,959
Yes, why not?

321
00:21:11,092 --> 00:21:12,458
PAUL:
Here, let me have it.

322
00:21:12,592 --> 00:21:15,092
- I'll fix everything.
- Thanks.

323
00:21:29,926 --> 00:21:31,293
[SIGHS]

324
00:21:33,692 --> 00:21:36,226
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

325
00:21:45,792 --> 00:21:48,226
Paul said
you weren't feeling very well.

326
00:21:49,826 --> 00:21:51,559
I'm fine, thank you.

327
00:21:56,492 --> 00:21:57,659
You look...

328
00:21:59,325 --> 00:22:00,458
worried.

329
00:22:02,293 --> 00:22:03,859
No, it's just, uh...

330
00:22:06,492 --> 00:22:07,826
Just what?

331
00:22:11,492 --> 00:22:12,859
Hey.

332
00:22:12,992 --> 00:22:14,126
[GROANS SOFTLY]

333
00:22:15,625 --> 00:22:16,792
Tell me.

334
00:22:18,792 --> 00:22:21,293
I was making a cup of tea
in the kitchen.

335
00:22:24,059 --> 00:22:27,959
I was alone in the flat,
and suddenly I heard... a noise.

336
00:22:28,092 --> 00:22:31,126
Then I came in here
and there was your husband.

337
00:22:31,259 --> 00:22:33,026
- Who?
- Hmm?

338
00:22:33,159 --> 00:22:35,525
- Your husband.
- What husband?

339
00:22:35,659 --> 00:22:37,458
Well, yours, my dear.
Not mine.

340
00:22:37,592 --> 00:22:38,659
James?

341
00:22:39,992 --> 00:22:41,126
Your husband.

342
00:22:41,259 --> 00:22:43,059
I'm not married, Dad.

343
00:22:43,193 --> 00:22:44,358
I'm sorry?

344
00:22:46,259 --> 00:22:48,293
I got divorced
more than five years ago.

345
00:22:48,425 --> 00:22:49,692
You remember.

346
00:22:51,959 --> 00:22:54,159
- Well, then, who's he?
- Well, who?

347
00:22:57,026 --> 00:22:58,458
Are you doing this on purpose?

348
00:22:58,592 --> 00:23:00,159
Him who just left
with the chicken.

349
00:23:00,293 --> 00:23:02,325
- The chicken?
- Did you not hand over a chicken

350
00:23:02,458 --> 00:23:05,193
- to someone a minute ago?
- What are you on about, Dad?

351
00:23:05,358 --> 00:23:07,325
Did you not hand over
a chicken to someone?

352
00:23:07,458 --> 00:23:09,092
- The chicken!
- What chicken?

353
00:23:09,226 --> 00:23:11,193
- [GRUNTS]
- What are you talking about, Dad?

354
00:23:23,059 --> 00:23:25,259
Well, he was here just now.

355
00:23:25,392 --> 00:23:28,625
I think you're mistaken, Dad.
There's no one here.

356
00:23:28,759 --> 00:23:30,859
- He's vanished.
- Who?

357
00:23:32,325 --> 00:23:33,859
The man with the chicken?

358
00:23:33,992 --> 00:23:36,026
- Your husband!
- [CHUCKLES]

359
00:23:36,159 --> 00:23:37,392
Why are you smiling?

360
00:23:37,525 --> 00:23:40,193
Nothing.
I'm sorry. Sorry.

361
00:23:42,625 --> 00:23:45,159
All this nonsense
is driving me crazy.

362
00:24:08,625 --> 00:24:09,692
[DOOR OPENS]

363
00:24:09,826 --> 00:24:11,259
What's the matter, Dad?

364
00:24:11,392 --> 00:24:12,792
[DOOR CLOSES]

365
00:24:14,425 --> 00:24:17,692
There's something
funny going on.

366
00:24:17,826 --> 00:24:21,193
Believe me, Anne, there is
something funny going on.

367
00:24:21,325 --> 00:24:23,659
- Come, sit down. Come on.
- Mm-hmm.

368
00:24:30,792 --> 00:24:33,259
Now, don't worry.

369
00:24:33,392 --> 00:24:37,425
Everything will
sort itself out. Hmm?

370
00:24:37,559 --> 00:24:39,226
I don't know.

371
00:24:39,358 --> 00:24:40,492
Yes, it will.

372
00:24:41,992 --> 00:24:43,358
Don't worry.

373
00:24:43,492 --> 00:24:45,193
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

374
00:24:45,358 --> 00:24:47,959
Have you taken
your medication?

375
00:24:48,092 --> 00:24:49,892
What's that got to do
with anything?

376
00:24:50,026 --> 00:24:51,525
Let's give you
your medication.

377
00:24:51,659 --> 00:24:53,325
The evening dose.

378
00:24:53,458 --> 00:24:55,026
Then you'll feel better.

379
00:24:56,959 --> 00:24:59,959
It's been going on
for some time.

380
00:25:00,092 --> 00:25:02,625
Strange things
going on around us.

381
00:25:02,759 --> 00:25:04,792
Haven't you noticed?

382
00:25:04,926 --> 00:25:06,826
[CHUCKLES]

383
00:25:06,959 --> 00:25:10,259
There was this man claiming
this was not my flat.

384
00:25:12,492 --> 00:25:14,859
A really
unsympathetic-looking man.

385
00:25:14,992 --> 00:25:16,959
A bit like your husband,
only worse.

386
00:25:18,792 --> 00:25:20,325
It's the best yet,
don't you think?

387
00:25:20,458 --> 00:25:22,525
In my flat. He told me.

388
00:25:28,759 --> 00:25:30,092
But, uh...

389
00:25:34,592 --> 00:25:36,458
This is my flat.

390
00:25:36,592 --> 00:25:37,959
Isn't it, hmm?

391
00:25:38,092 --> 00:25:39,126
Anne?

392
00:25:41,792 --> 00:25:43,525
Isn't it?

393
00:25:43,659 --> 00:25:46,358
Tell me, Anne,
this really is my flat.

394
00:25:48,026 --> 00:25:49,026
Isn't it?

395
00:25:51,692 --> 00:25:52,992
Oh.

396
00:25:57,926 --> 00:25:59,226
[SIPS WATER]

397
00:26:00,592 --> 00:26:01,792
Thank you.

398
00:26:03,092 --> 00:26:04,992
[♪♪♪]

399
00:26:15,959 --> 00:26:17,126
[DOOR OPENS]

400
00:26:18,325 --> 00:26:20,159
ANNE:
Yeah.

401
00:26:20,293 --> 00:26:21,259
I know.

402
00:26:21,392 --> 00:26:22,826
[DOOR CLOSES]

403
00:26:22,959 --> 00:26:24,325
I know.

404
00:26:24,458 --> 00:26:27,259
No. You can't imagine
how difficult it is sometimes.

405
00:26:27,392 --> 00:26:30,193
The other day,
he didn't even recognize me.

406
00:26:30,325 --> 00:26:32,293
Oh, I know.

407
00:26:32,425 --> 00:26:33,325
Yeah.

408
00:26:34,392 --> 00:26:36,425
Thank you.

409
00:26:36,559 --> 00:26:39,425
As long as he likes her,
that's the main thing, isn't it?

410
00:26:39,559 --> 00:26:42,458
And to know that he'll...
He'll be happy.

411
00:26:43,625 --> 00:26:44,659
Yeah.

412
00:26:46,826 --> 00:26:49,325
No, that's a good idea.
Yeah, absolutely.

413
00:26:49,458 --> 00:26:51,159
Hope so.

414
00:26:51,293 --> 00:26:53,293
She seemed nice on the phone.

415
00:26:54,926 --> 00:26:56,992
[LAUGHS]

416
00:26:57,126 --> 00:26:59,959
Well, I'll let you know
how it goes.

417
00:27:00,092 --> 00:27:01,458
Yeah.

418
00:27:01,592 --> 00:27:02,692
Okay.

419
00:27:03,959 --> 00:27:05,659
Right, right.

420
00:27:05,792 --> 00:27:08,625
Okay. Speak soon.
Lots of love. Bye.

421
00:27:08,759 --> 00:27:10,358
[PENCIL SCRATCHING]

422
00:27:14,092 --> 00:27:15,358
[DOORBELL RINGS]

423
00:27:26,092 --> 00:27:28,358
- Hello.
- Hello. I'm not too early, am I?

424
00:27:28,492 --> 00:27:30,792
No, no, not at all.
Come in.

425
00:27:30,926 --> 00:27:32,259
- Come in.
- Thanks.

426
00:27:34,325 --> 00:27:35,592
So come in.

427
00:27:35,725 --> 00:27:37,926
- Thanks for coming around.
- That's okay.

428
00:27:38,059 --> 00:27:40,358
Um, my father's, uh,
just in his room.

429
00:27:40,492 --> 00:27:42,026
Would you like
something to drink?

430
00:27:42,159 --> 00:27:43,259
- No, thanks.
- Okay.

431
00:27:43,392 --> 00:27:45,192
Please make
yourself comfortable.

432
00:27:45,325 --> 00:27:46,826
I, um...

433
00:27:46,959 --> 00:27:48,392
Yeah, so I was telling you,

434
00:27:48,525 --> 00:27:50,859
my father is quite upset
by the whole idea...

435
00:27:50,992 --> 00:27:55,859
- That's okay.
- Yeah, so it can cause him to...

436
00:27:55,992 --> 00:27:58,559
Uh, I think he's quite
annoyed with me, heh.

437
00:27:58,692 --> 00:28:01,525
I'm just telling you this
because, uh, he is capable

438
00:28:01,659 --> 00:28:03,692
of reacting unexpectedly.

439
00:28:03,826 --> 00:28:05,826
Has he lived on his own
up till now?

440
00:28:05,959 --> 00:28:10,392
Yes. Uh, yeah, he was in a flat
not far from here. Which worked.

441
00:28:10,525 --> 00:28:13,059
And I was able to pop in on him
practically every day.

442
00:28:13,193 --> 00:28:15,293
But we've had to come
to another arrangement.

443
00:28:15,425 --> 00:28:18,026
- It just wasn't viable anymore.
- I understand.

444
00:28:18,159 --> 00:28:22,325
Um, and he's had several carers,
one after another.

445
00:28:22,458 --> 00:28:25,525
Um, he finds it difficult
to get on with them.

446
00:28:25,659 --> 00:28:27,126
He has his ways. Heh.

447
00:28:27,259 --> 00:28:29,959
- [CHUCKLES SOFTLY]
- Uh, so that's why I moved him

448
00:28:30,092 --> 00:28:31,659
in here with me.

449
00:28:31,792 --> 00:28:34,358
But I'm finding it quite
difficult to manage on my own.

450
00:28:34,492 --> 00:28:36,325
It's a bit much
'cause I have to work,

451
00:28:36,458 --> 00:28:38,659
and that's why
I need someone to help me.

452
00:28:38,792 --> 00:28:40,193
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

453
00:28:40,325 --> 00:28:42,026
- Did I hear the bell?
- Dad. Yes.

454
00:28:42,159 --> 00:28:44,026
- Ding-dong.
- [ANNE CHUCKLES]

455
00:28:44,159 --> 00:28:46,458
- I'd like you to meet Laura.
- How do you do, sir?

456
00:28:46,592 --> 00:28:49,193
I explained to you that Laura
was going to come by today

457
00:28:49,325 --> 00:28:50,559
so that you two could meet.

458
00:28:50,692 --> 00:28:52,125
- Hello.
- Hello.

459
00:28:52,259 --> 00:28:54,725
- I say, you're gorgeous.
- Thank you.

460
00:28:54,859 --> 00:28:56,358
But I, um...

461
00:28:58,126 --> 00:28:59,892
Haven't we met before?

462
00:29:00,026 --> 00:29:01,625
- No, I don't think so.
- Are you sure?

463
00:29:01,759 --> 00:29:04,625
I have a distinct impression
that I've seen you before.

464
00:29:04,759 --> 00:29:07,959
So Laura has come round,
uh, to meet us

465
00:29:08,092 --> 00:29:09,826
so she can get
an idea of how you live

466
00:29:09,959 --> 00:29:12,226
and to what extent
she might be able to help you.

467
00:29:12,392 --> 00:29:13,559
I know, dear.
I know that.

468
00:29:13,692 --> 00:29:16,026
You've already told me
a hundred times.

469
00:29:16,159 --> 00:29:18,026
My daughter has, um...

470
00:29:18,159 --> 00:29:20,026
a tendency
to repeat herself.

471
00:29:20,159 --> 00:29:22,358
But you know what it's like,
it's an age thing.

472
00:29:22,492 --> 00:29:24,692
- [LAUGHS]
- Would you like a drink?

473
00:29:24,826 --> 00:29:26,325
You're very kind,
but no, thanks.

474
00:29:26,458 --> 00:29:29,026
An aperitif? Are you sure?
A little aperitif.

475
00:29:29,159 --> 00:29:31,358
- Time for an aperitif, no, no?
- [LAUGHS]

476
00:29:31,492 --> 00:29:34,126
Oh, hang...
Just a moment, I'll be back.

477
00:29:36,259 --> 00:29:39,159
- He's going to find his watch.
- Oh.

478
00:29:39,293 --> 00:29:42,826
- I must say, he's charming.
- Yeah. Not always.

479
00:29:42,959 --> 00:29:44,458
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

480
00:29:53,592 --> 00:29:57,159
Just as I thought, time
for an aperitif! Ha-ha-ha!

481
00:29:57,293 --> 00:29:59,126
I have two watches.
I've always had two.

482
00:29:59,259 --> 00:30:01,559
One on my wrist
and the other in my head. Bup!

483
00:30:01,692 --> 00:30:03,059
It's always been that way.

484
00:30:03,193 --> 00:30:05,226
Now, what would you like,
young lady?

485
00:30:05,358 --> 00:30:06,659
Dad.

486
00:30:06,792 --> 00:30:09,525
I'm allowed to offer
our guest a drink, am I not?

487
00:30:09,659 --> 00:30:11,193
What will it be?

488
00:30:12,859 --> 00:30:14,892
- What are you going to have?
- A small whiskey.

489
00:30:15,026 --> 00:30:17,692
- Then I'll have the same.
- Boom! Splendid.

490
00:30:17,826 --> 00:30:20,159
Two small whiskies coming up.

491
00:30:21,325 --> 00:30:22,525
Anne, please.

492
00:30:24,226 --> 00:30:26,859
It's okay, Anne, I'm not
going to offer you a drink.

493
00:30:26,992 --> 00:30:29,026
She never touches alcohol.
Not a drop.

494
00:30:29,159 --> 00:30:31,659
- It's true.
- Never. Not a drop, yeah.

495
00:30:31,792 --> 00:30:34,826
Um, that's why
she seems so, uh...

496
00:30:34,959 --> 00:30:36,525
- So what?
- Um, sober.

497
00:30:36,659 --> 00:30:38,126
Her mother was,
uh, the same.

498
00:30:38,259 --> 00:30:39,992
The soberest woman
I've ever met.

499
00:30:40,126 --> 00:30:41,859
[ANTHONY & LAURA LAUGH]

500
00:30:43,226 --> 00:30:44,759
Oh, dear. Heh-heh.

501
00:30:44,892 --> 00:30:47,259
Silly. Um, whereas
her little sister

502
00:30:47,392 --> 00:30:49,992
- was quite a different story.
- Oh, you have two daughters?

503
00:30:50,126 --> 00:30:52,492
Even though I hardly ever hear
from the other one.

504
00:30:52,625 --> 00:30:54,492
All the same,
she was always my favorite.

505
00:30:54,625 --> 00:30:56,458
She was a painter.
Look, there you are.

506
00:30:56,592 --> 00:30:58,792
<i>The Pirouette.</i>
Beautiful, isn't it?

507
00:30:58,926 --> 00:30:59,959
Yes, it is.

508
00:31:00,092 --> 00:31:01,226
ANTHONY:
Yes.

509
00:31:02,759 --> 00:31:04,492
A dazzling girl.

510
00:31:04,625 --> 00:31:07,325
I don't understand why
she never gets in touch. Never.

511
00:31:08,525 --> 00:31:10,692
- [GLASSES CLINK]
- Your whiskey.

512
00:31:10,826 --> 00:31:12,126
- Thank you.
- Cheers.

513
00:31:15,959 --> 00:31:17,193
[GROANS, CHUCKLES]

514
00:31:17,325 --> 00:31:18,392
[SUCKS TEETH]

515
00:31:18,525 --> 00:31:20,859
Mmm. Ah!

516
00:31:20,992 --> 00:31:22,293
I'd give everything I own

517
00:31:22,425 --> 00:31:24,259
for a glass of whiskey.
Don't you agree?

518
00:31:24,392 --> 00:31:26,358
Well, I don't own
all that much, so...

519
00:31:26,492 --> 00:31:28,826
Oh, really? What do you do
for a living?

520
00:31:30,159 --> 00:31:33,159
Um, I look after
other people.

521
00:31:33,293 --> 00:31:34,659
Other people?

522
00:31:34,792 --> 00:31:37,358
Mm, yeah, my job is to
help people who need help.

523
00:31:37,492 --> 00:31:39,193
Heh, oh!

524
00:31:39,325 --> 00:31:42,325
Sounds like those girls you're
always trying to dump off on me.

525
00:31:42,458 --> 00:31:44,325
Must be a difficult job
though, isn't it?

526
00:31:44,458 --> 00:31:46,159
Spending all day
with one of those...

527
00:31:46,293 --> 00:31:48,159
Ugh! I couldn't stand it.
Am I right?

528
00:31:48,293 --> 00:31:49,859
[BOTH LAUGHING]

529
00:31:49,992 --> 00:31:52,126
What about you?
What did you do for a living?

530
00:31:52,259 --> 00:31:53,792
Oh, I was a dancer.

531
00:31:53,926 --> 00:31:54,859
- Were you?
- Yes.

532
00:31:54,992 --> 00:31:56,992
- Dad.
- What?

533
00:31:57,126 --> 00:32:00,525
- You were an engineer.
- What do you know about it?

534
00:32:00,659 --> 00:32:02,659
Yes, tap dancing
was my specialty.

535
00:32:02,792 --> 00:32:04,826
- Really?
- You seem surprised.

536
00:32:04,959 --> 00:32:06,659
- A little bit.
- Why?

537
00:32:06,792 --> 00:32:09,692
Don't you believe me, or you
find that difficult to imagine?

538
00:32:09,826 --> 00:32:13,325
Of course. It's just...
I've always loved tap dancing.

539
00:32:13,458 --> 00:32:16,559
You, really? I'm still
great at it. I'll show you.

540
00:32:16,692 --> 00:32:18,226
[SNAPPING FINGERS]

541
00:32:18,358 --> 00:32:21,293
- [LAUGHING]
- Ay! Ha-ha!

542
00:32:21,425 --> 00:32:23,992
Jolly good.
Why are you laughing?

543
00:32:24,126 --> 00:32:26,092
Nothing.
Sorry. Sorry.

544
00:32:26,226 --> 00:32:28,159
I know...
I know who she reminds me of.

545
00:32:28,293 --> 00:32:29,759
- Who?
- It's Lucy.

546
00:32:29,892 --> 00:32:31,759
- Lucy, when she was younger.
- Lucy?

547
00:32:31,892 --> 00:32:33,692
Yeah, my other daughter.
That's right.

548
00:32:33,826 --> 00:32:35,659
There is a resemblance,
don't you think?

549
00:32:35,792 --> 00:32:37,759
- Yeah, maybe.
- Yes.

550
00:32:37,892 --> 00:32:40,293
- [LAUGHING]
- Yes.

551
00:32:40,425 --> 00:32:42,792
Her unbearable habit
of laughing inanely.

552
00:32:47,792 --> 00:32:49,358
I had you there, didn't I?

553
00:32:49,492 --> 00:32:51,159
[ANTHONY LAUGHS]

554
00:32:55,126 --> 00:32:57,692
You see, the situation
is very simple.

555
00:32:57,826 --> 00:33:00,293
I have lived in this flat...

556
00:33:00,425 --> 00:33:02,159
for some time now.

557
00:33:02,293 --> 00:33:04,625
I'm extremely
attached to it.

558
00:33:04,759 --> 00:33:06,792
And I bought it
more than 30 years ago.

559
00:33:06,926 --> 00:33:09,559
Can you imagine?
You weren't even born.

560
00:33:09,692 --> 00:33:11,325
Yes, it's a big flat.

561
00:33:11,458 --> 00:33:14,126
Very nice. It's very big.

562
00:33:14,259 --> 00:33:17,725
And, uh, I've been
very happy here.

563
00:33:17,859 --> 00:33:23,126
Uh, anyway, my daughter
is very interested in it.

564
00:33:23,259 --> 00:33:24,892
ANNE:
What are you talking about?

565
00:33:25,026 --> 00:33:27,059
You see, my daughter
is of the opinion

566
00:33:27,193 --> 00:33:29,126
that I cannot manage
on my own.

567
00:33:29,259 --> 00:33:32,026
So she's moved in with me,
ostensibly to help me,

568
00:33:32,159 --> 00:33:37,092
with this man she met not
long ago just after her divorce.

569
00:33:37,226 --> 00:33:40,592
Yeah. Who has
a very bad influence on her,

570
00:33:40,725 --> 00:33:43,492
- I have to tell you.
- What are you talking about, Dad?

571
00:33:43,625 --> 00:33:45,625
So now she would like
to convince me

572
00:33:45,759 --> 00:33:49,126
that I really cannot
manage on my own.

573
00:33:49,259 --> 00:33:52,792
And, uh, the next stage
will be to send me away.

574
00:33:52,926 --> 00:33:55,592
I don't know where. It'll be
a much more efficient way

575
00:33:55,725 --> 00:33:57,659
of getting hold of my flat.

576
00:33:57,792 --> 00:34:01,659
But, um, it's not
going to happen that way.

577
00:34:01,792 --> 00:34:03,792
[ANTHONY CHUCKLES]

578
00:34:03,926 --> 00:34:06,826
Sorry, dear.
I may as well tell you now.

579
00:34:08,358 --> 00:34:11,492
I'm not leaving
this flat any time soon.

580
00:34:11,625 --> 00:34:14,959
I'm going to outlive you.

581
00:34:15,092 --> 00:34:16,525
Both of you.

582
00:34:16,659 --> 00:34:18,792
I don't know about you...

583
00:34:18,926 --> 00:34:20,959
but my daughter, yes.

584
00:34:21,092 --> 00:34:22,325
[CHUCKLES]

585
00:34:22,458 --> 00:34:24,458
In fact, I'm gonna
make a point about it.

586
00:34:24,592 --> 00:34:28,126
I'm going to inherit from her.
Not the other way around.

587
00:34:28,259 --> 00:34:31,959
And, uh, the day of her funeral,
I shall give a little speech.

588
00:34:32,092 --> 00:34:33,959
Uh, to remind everyone
how heartless

589
00:34:34,092 --> 00:34:35,792
and, uh, manipulative she was.

590
00:34:35,926 --> 00:34:39,826
- I'm so sorry about this.
- Why? She understands perfectly.

591
00:34:39,959 --> 00:34:41,325
You're the one who doesn't.

592
00:34:41,458 --> 00:34:44,293
See, I've been trying
to convince her for months

593
00:34:44,425 --> 00:34:47,026
that I can manage
very well on my own.

594
00:34:47,159 --> 00:34:50,193
But... she refuses to listen.

595
00:34:51,492 --> 00:34:56,458
I don't need
any help from anyone.

596
00:34:56,592 --> 00:34:59,759
And I'm not
going to leave my flat.

597
00:34:59,892 --> 00:35:02,293
All I want is for everyone
to fuck off.

598
00:35:03,692 --> 00:35:05,059
Having said that...

599
00:35:06,492 --> 00:35:08,325
it's been a great pleasure.

600
00:35:08,458 --> 00:35:10,226
Au revoir. Toodle-oo.

601
00:35:13,792 --> 00:35:16,392
I'm really
very sorry about this.

602
00:35:16,525 --> 00:35:18,859
You weren't kidding
when you said he had his ways.

603
00:35:18,992 --> 00:35:20,325
I'm really sorry.

604
00:35:21,826 --> 00:35:26,026
Don't be. That sort
of reaction's quite normal.

605
00:35:28,425 --> 00:35:30,325
It'll be all right.

606
00:35:30,458 --> 00:35:31,625
Do you think?

607
00:35:37,592 --> 00:35:38,659
Yeah.

608
00:35:42,759 --> 00:35:44,659
[♪♪♪]

609
00:35:48,492 --> 00:35:49,792
[SIGHS]

610
00:35:49,926 --> 00:35:52,425
[WATER TURNS ON, OFF]

611
00:36:09,759 --> 00:36:11,126
[SNIFFLES]

612
00:36:22,759 --> 00:36:24,992
[SOBS]

613
00:36:25,126 --> 00:36:26,559
[SNIFFLING]

614
00:37:31,525 --> 00:37:32,959
PAUL:
Well?

615
00:37:34,026 --> 00:37:35,458
What?

616
00:37:35,592 --> 00:37:36,992
- Did it go well?
- Um...

617
00:37:38,392 --> 00:37:39,959
Yeah.

618
00:37:40,092 --> 00:37:42,425
I think so. She said
she was gonna start tomorrow.

619
00:37:42,559 --> 00:37:44,193
- Here?
- Yeah.

620
00:37:44,325 --> 00:37:45,859
Good.

621
00:37:45,992 --> 00:37:49,092
Yeah. So we'll see
how the first day goes, and...

622
00:37:49,226 --> 00:37:51,325
I was really worried
it wasn't gonna work,

623
00:37:51,458 --> 00:37:53,159
but in the end,
it was fine.

624
00:37:53,293 --> 00:37:55,926
- He was charming.
- Oh, there you are, you see.

625
00:37:57,725 --> 00:38:00,325
Yeah. He really
turned the charm on for her.

626
00:38:00,458 --> 00:38:02,092
You should have seen him.

627
00:38:02,226 --> 00:38:05,659
He told her he'd been
a dancer. A tap dancer.

628
00:38:05,792 --> 00:38:07,325
- No.
- Yeah.

629
00:38:09,293 --> 00:38:11,059
I don't know
how to describe it to you.

630
00:38:11,193 --> 00:38:13,226
I think she's really
going to be able to...

631
00:38:13,358 --> 00:38:16,625
I think they're really
gonna get on well together.

632
00:38:18,525 --> 00:38:20,859
And then he said
that she reminded him of Lucy.

633
00:38:22,193 --> 00:38:23,325
Really?

634
00:38:25,325 --> 00:38:27,159
How old is she?

635
00:38:27,293 --> 00:38:28,725
Why, you interested?

636
00:38:40,126 --> 00:38:41,659
What's the matter with you?

637
00:38:43,826 --> 00:38:46,092
If it went well,
that's good news, isn't it?

638
00:38:47,159 --> 00:38:48,692
Yes. Yeah.

639
00:38:48,826 --> 00:38:50,092
So?

640
00:38:51,892 --> 00:38:53,592
What's the matter with you?
Tell me.

641
00:38:53,725 --> 00:38:55,193
It's just...

642
00:38:55,325 --> 00:38:56,926
What?

643
00:38:57,059 --> 00:38:59,092
Just now, when I came back
with the chicken,

644
00:38:59,226 --> 00:39:01,659
he didn't recognize me.

645
00:39:01,792 --> 00:39:03,959
I don't know,
it just did something to me.

646
00:39:06,226 --> 00:39:07,492
I understand.

647
00:39:07,625 --> 00:39:09,193
Finding it really hard.

648
00:39:10,759 --> 00:39:12,392
Come, give me a hug.

649
00:39:17,259 --> 00:39:19,458
I saw it in his eyes.
He didn't know who I was.

650
00:39:19,592 --> 00:39:21,392
It was like
I was a stranger to him.

651
00:39:23,126 --> 00:39:25,792
- You'll have to get used to it.
- I can't manage to.

652
00:39:25,926 --> 00:39:29,892
I think you can. I think
you're managing really well.

653
00:39:30,026 --> 00:39:31,293
Come on.

654
00:39:33,826 --> 00:39:35,126
[SIGHS]

655
00:39:36,193 --> 00:39:38,525
ANNE:
Oh, Dad. Hi.

656
00:39:38,659 --> 00:39:41,492
Dinner will be ready in five
minutes. Does that suit you?

657
00:39:41,625 --> 00:39:44,692
Yes, dear.
Suits me fine.

658
00:39:44,826 --> 00:39:47,592
Suits me fine. Hello.

659
00:39:50,092 --> 00:39:51,325
Are you hungry?

660
00:39:52,659 --> 00:39:54,492
Yes, yes. But, uh...

661
00:39:56,059 --> 00:39:58,358
We have guests
this evening?

662
00:39:58,492 --> 00:40:00,159
No, why?

663
00:40:01,226 --> 00:40:02,325
Oh, nothing.

664
00:40:03,592 --> 00:40:04,792
Nothing.

665
00:40:04,926 --> 00:40:06,826
[♪♪♪]

666
00:40:25,458 --> 00:40:26,959
Everything all right?

667
00:40:28,425 --> 00:40:29,725
You had a good day?

668
00:40:29,859 --> 00:40:31,293
Yeah, very good.

669
00:40:31,425 --> 00:40:32,892
Laura came by.

670
00:40:33,026 --> 00:40:35,358
Didn't she, Dad? Laura came by
just now to see us.

671
00:40:35,492 --> 00:40:37,358
- Who?
- Laura.

672
00:40:37,492 --> 00:40:39,159
The young woman
who came to see us.

673
00:40:39,293 --> 00:40:40,325
ANTHONY:
Mmm.

674
00:40:43,092 --> 00:40:45,592
- Then we went to the doctor.
- Has anyone seen my watch?

675
00:40:45,725 --> 00:40:48,425
- I seem to have lost it. Uh...
- ANNE: Again?

676
00:40:48,559 --> 00:40:50,358
You've probably put it
in your cupboard.

677
00:40:50,492 --> 00:40:52,592
- In your hiding place.
- What cupboard?

678
00:40:52,725 --> 00:40:54,492
I don't know
what you're talking about.

679
00:40:54,625 --> 00:40:56,625
I really don't know,
Anne.

680
00:40:56,759 --> 00:40:58,358
What cupboard?
There's no cupboard.

681
00:40:58,492 --> 00:41:00,826
There's no cupboard,
is there? Ha-ha!

682
00:41:00,959 --> 00:41:02,492
[QUIETLY]
Can we be more discreet?

683
00:41:02,625 --> 00:41:04,126
Have you looked
in your cupboard?

684
00:41:04,259 --> 00:41:06,759
It's not there.
I must have lost it somewhere.

685
00:41:06,892 --> 00:41:08,358
- Or it's been stolen.
- It hasn't.

686
00:41:08,492 --> 00:41:11,425
What do you mean, it hasn't?
It can't have flown away.

687
00:41:11,559 --> 00:41:14,659
- Want me to go and have a look?
- Very much so. It is a bother.

688
00:41:14,792 --> 00:41:17,725
I am worried.
It's very worrying. I mean...

689
00:41:17,859 --> 00:41:21,193
Losing all my things, everyone's
just helping themselves, and...

690
00:41:21,325 --> 00:41:25,458
If this goes on much longer,
um, I'll be stark naked.

691
00:41:25,592 --> 00:41:27,859
And, um, I...

692
00:41:27,992 --> 00:41:30,525
I won't be able to tell
what time it is. Please.

693
00:41:30,659 --> 00:41:31,959
Thank you.

694
00:41:35,692 --> 00:41:37,659
[WHISTLING SOFTLY]

695
00:42:07,392 --> 00:42:08,859
Might you have the time?

696
00:42:11,259 --> 00:42:12,859
- Almost eight.
- Oh.

697
00:42:13,926 --> 00:42:15,126
That's late.

698
00:42:16,458 --> 00:42:18,492
Shouldn't we be
sitting down for dinner?

699
00:42:18,625 --> 00:42:21,859
Yes, in five minutes,
uh, when the chicken's ready.

700
00:42:21,992 --> 00:42:24,392
We're having chicken
this evening?

701
00:42:24,525 --> 00:42:26,525
- It's the one Anne bought.
- Ha!

702
00:42:31,293 --> 00:42:32,692
[TICKING]

703
00:42:40,492 --> 00:42:42,325
It's pretty.

704
00:42:42,458 --> 00:42:44,625
Your watch, it's, um...

705
00:42:44,759 --> 00:42:47,525
It's very pretty.
It's, uh...

706
00:42:47,659 --> 00:42:49,659
Yeah. Is it yours?

707
00:42:49,792 --> 00:42:53,259
Ha, I... I mean,
is it, uh, yours?

708
00:42:53,392 --> 00:42:55,293
Mm, yes.

709
00:42:56,425 --> 00:42:57,826
Might I see it?
It's, uh...

710
00:42:57,959 --> 00:43:00,959
So, apparently,
it went very well today.

711
00:43:01,092 --> 00:43:02,659
Oh, yes.

712
00:43:04,159 --> 00:43:05,759
Very well. Very well.

713
00:43:07,625 --> 00:43:10,159
Apparently,
she looks like Lucy.

714
00:43:10,293 --> 00:43:12,159
Really?

715
00:43:12,293 --> 00:43:14,592
I don't know.
I've never seen her.

716
00:43:14,725 --> 00:43:16,193
No, it, um...

717
00:43:18,092 --> 00:43:20,625
It went well. Anne seemed
pleased. You know, it's...

718
00:43:20,759 --> 00:43:23,992
I don't really need...
It's mainly for Anne.

719
00:43:25,525 --> 00:43:27,492
Might I have a look at it?
See your watch?

720
00:43:27,625 --> 00:43:31,492
You're right, you know, it's
important to her this works out.

721
00:43:31,625 --> 00:43:33,725
- Yeah.
- Anthony, um,

722
00:43:33,859 --> 00:43:35,659
she's been worried
about you.

723
00:43:35,792 --> 00:43:38,325
And it really upsets her

724
00:43:38,458 --> 00:43:40,859
when you keep
falling out with...

725
00:43:43,293 --> 00:43:45,358
- What is it about my watch?
- Oh, nothing.

726
00:43:45,492 --> 00:43:47,692
I was just, uh, looking.

727
00:43:47,826 --> 00:43:49,959
I want to check it's, um...

728
00:43:50,092 --> 00:43:53,293
Check if it's, uh...
It's pretty. Very pretty.

729
00:43:55,092 --> 00:43:57,026
- Did you buy it?
- Sorry?

730
00:43:57,159 --> 00:44:00,193
Um, was it a present
or did you buy it?

731
00:44:00,325 --> 00:44:01,692
I bought it.

732
00:44:01,826 --> 00:44:04,293
- Oh.
- Why?

733
00:44:04,425 --> 00:44:06,625
I don't suppose
you kept the receipt?

734
00:44:06,759 --> 00:44:08,159
What are you talking about?

735
00:44:08,293 --> 00:44:11,425
- Your watch. It's, uh...
- I was talking about Anne.

736
00:44:12,992 --> 00:44:15,525
- Anne?
- Ye...

737
00:44:15,659 --> 00:44:17,092
Yes, Anne.

738
00:44:17,226 --> 00:44:18,492
Yeah.

739
00:44:30,659 --> 00:44:31,892
[BLOWS]

740
00:44:44,193 --> 00:44:47,193
ANTHONY: I don't know why we
never really got on well together.

741
00:44:49,525 --> 00:44:51,826
Whereas her little sister...

742
00:44:51,959 --> 00:44:54,625
Ah, that was another story.

743
00:44:56,892 --> 00:45:00,259
Do you know her?
Um, she's marvelous.

744
00:45:00,392 --> 00:45:02,126
Marvelous.

745
00:45:02,259 --> 00:45:04,325
I haven't seen her
for months.

746
00:45:07,059 --> 00:45:09,425
I can't blame her,
she's, uh...

747
00:45:09,559 --> 00:45:12,692
traveling around the world,
I think.

748
00:45:12,826 --> 00:45:14,425
She's a painter.

749
00:45:16,992 --> 00:45:20,859
I'd be so happy
if she came to see me one day.

750
00:45:20,992 --> 00:45:22,325
[CHUCKLES]

751
00:45:22,458 --> 00:45:23,959
I'd take her in my arms

752
00:45:24,092 --> 00:45:28,226
and we'd be glued
to one another.

753
00:45:28,358 --> 00:45:31,293
For hours on end,
like we used to be.

754
00:45:31,425 --> 00:45:33,458
A long time ago,
when she was little.

755
00:45:35,959 --> 00:45:39,692
When she still used
to call me:

756
00:45:39,826 --> 00:45:41,226
"Little Daddy."

757
00:45:42,625 --> 00:45:44,159
"Little Daddy."

758
00:45:44,293 --> 00:45:45,625
Now, that's...

759
00:45:47,592 --> 00:45:50,559
That's what she used to call me,
you know?

760
00:45:50,692 --> 00:45:52,625
Nice, isn't it?
"Little Daddy."

761
00:45:56,625 --> 00:45:58,458
Can I ask you
a question?

762
00:45:58,592 --> 00:45:59,659
Mmm?

763
00:46:01,293 --> 00:46:03,926
But I want
an honest answer.

764
00:46:04,059 --> 00:46:05,358
Nothing fancy.

765
00:46:06,592 --> 00:46:08,525
Can you do that
for me?

766
